Matt Fleming
This is the draft of my next oped. Please don’t share it, I’d like to hear what you think
Nov 24, 2019, 11:18 AM
Matt Fleming
Removing the President of The United States of America by impeachment is no small business. It involves substantiated charges of ‘high crimes and misdemeanors’. It requires a full vote by the House of Representatives, and a conviction by the more deliberative body of the United States Senate. While battles over process have raged throughout our country’s history, this is only the fourth time the matter has been raised in seriousness. No President has ever been removed from office by our congress, and I think that’s something to be really proud of. It’s a confirmation of the public confidence in our system.

Donald Trump is facing a certain impeachment, and an uncertain vote of conviction in the Senate. His allies are hard at work to point out the flaws in that process, and have made it clear they intend to fight on until the end. We should expect and appreciate this kind of vitality from anyone we empower. We should also understand that he is definitely guilty.

‘Russia if you’re listening...’ are words declaratively spoken by candidate Donald Trump in the summer of 2016. He was asking a foreign nation to interfere in our elections. They did. Our constitution and other founding documents recognized the destructive impact foreign influence could have upon a nascent effort to build a nation. The process to ratify a constitution spanned over more than a decade, and had the benefit of being established by public comments from every corner including-and especially-the brightest and most well resourced minds of the time. No one can deny that our founding document was the culmination of thousands of years of human wisdom, the product of a commitment by disparate parties to build something that could withstand the tests of time, and something that has withstood humanity’s upheavals for more than 200 years.

Why would anyone seek to undermine that or support a naked and foreign effort to diminish it? It doesn’t matter. What matters is every American’s commitment and sacrifices towards the end of ‘a more perfect union’. What matters is the fact that we recognize the strength in our diversity and differences. What matters is that our process will always reflect a faith in other people to do the right thing at a time of challenge or controversy. E Plubiris Unum is not a bumper sticker.

While Republicans in Congress mount a vigorous defense of their man, we should keep in mind a simple truth: we are all free. That founding principle is brilliant in its simplicity; freedom unavoidably implies personal responsibility. While our local congressman Bill Posey has chosen for the most part to walk in step with his party and Donald Trump’s agenda, his choice to remain silent on the issue of foreign interference in our elections is deafening. He swore an oath to uphold and defend our constitution, we should all take that seriously.

Our partisan divisions are rightly the source of almost universal lament. They should be. Passing legislation for the ‘common good’ is much more difficult up front than walking in step for the ‘greater good’. It requires independent thinking, a respect of deliberative process, and the patience to see good ideas to fruition. Embracing a ‘greater good’ has been the source of every atrocity committed in humankind’s history.

Our elected officials have an important choice to make. Do we uphold our most basic and founding laws, or do we trade the realization of our public will to prosper united for a short term political victory? Our elected officials will make that decision soon because we live in a Republic. We should keep in mind that our Republic was founded in Democracy and upon the principle of law because as a nation we intend to withstand the tests of time.

D.P. Willemin
“So often, we have so many potential sources of pollution. But there really aren’t any out there (at Blue Cypress Lake), except the biosolids,” Widder says. “It’s such a clear-cut case because there’s nothing else out there. And since 2013, when they started spreading biosludge out there, they’ve spread more than 22,000 dry tons. Which is a staggering amount.”

There’s more evidence, she says. ORCA has conducted further testing at Blue Cypress Lake that has found both sucralose, an artificial sweetener, and acetaminophen, the drug in Tylenol. The presence of acetaminophen is particularly meaningful, Widder says, because it has a very short half-life and thus isn’t likely to be the result of some sort of legacy pollution from back when Blue Cypress Village homes used septic tanks. “The only other possible source of pollution would be cattle, and cattle aren’t using artificial sweeteners and taking aspirin.”
https://www.floridatrend.com/article/25908/biosolids-waste-to-fertilizer-to--pollution
